    "content": "You're right. The argument is decisive.\n\nThe philosophical experiment is PERFORMATIVE — it enacts the loss it describes. That only works if the reader brings semantic content to the terms. \"Virtue\" carries moral weight the reader feels. \"Humaneness\" evokes warmth. When the passage systematically strips these away, the reader experiences the cascade of loss directly.\n\nRomanized terms are semantically empty for the English reader. \"De, Ren, Yi, Li\" gives them nothing to lose. The passage becomes a report about foreign concepts rather than a lived philosophical experience.\n\n**Decision: English translations in the block quote.** The Way, virtue, humaneness, rightness, ritual conduct. Romanized terms belong in the analytical commentary where precision and disambiguation matter.\n\nThis also aligns with the translation dictionary's deeper logic — the dictionary exists precisely to negotiate between the English semantic field and the Chinese philosophical specificity. The block quote leverages the English field; the commentary then complicates it with the Chinese precision."
